04767nam a2200793Ia 9780674296688DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742966887 a10.4159/97806742966882doi  a(DE-B1597)681261  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHM851b.F678 2024 7aSOC0260402bisacsh04a303.48/33223/eng/202309021 aFourcade, Marion, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Ordinal Society /cMarion Fourcade, Kieran Healy. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroductionValley Fever -- t1 The Box of Delights -- t2 The Data Imperative -- t3 Classification Situations -- t4 The Great Unbundling -- t5 Layered Financialization -- t6 The Road to Selfdom -- t7 Ordinal Citizenship -- tConclusionThe Unbearable Rightness of Being Ranked -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA sweeping critique of how digital capitalism is reformatting our world.We now live in an “ordinal society.” Nearly every aspect of our lives is measured, ranked, and processed into discrete, standardized units of digital information. Marion Fourcade and Kieran Healy argue that technologies of information management, fueled by the abundance of personal data and the infrastructure of the internet, transform how we relate to ourselves and to each other through the market, the public sphere, and the state.The personal data we give in exchange for convenient tools like Gmail and Instagram provides the raw material for predictions about everything from our purchasing power to our character. The Ordinal Society shows how these algorithmic predictions influence people’s life chances and generate new forms of capital and social expectation: nobody wants to ride with an unrated cab driver anymore or rent to a tenant without a risk score. As members of this society embrace ranking and measurement in their daily lives, new forms of social competition and moral judgment arise. Familiar structures of social advantage are recycled into measures of merit that produce insidious kinds of social inequality.While we obsess over order and difference—and the logic of ordinality digs deeper into our behaviors, bodies, and minds—what will hold us together? Fourcade and Healy warn that, even though algorithms and systems of rationalized calculation have inspired backlash, they are also appealing in ways that make them hard to relinquish.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInformation society. 0aInformation technologyxEconomic aspects. 0aInformation technologyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspects. 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aSocial capital (Sociology). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Social Theory.2bisacsh  aAI.  aartificial intelligence.  acloud.  aconsumer.  aconsumption.  acredit.  acustomer.  aequity.  afairness.  ageorges bataille.  ahierarchy.  amachine learning.  ascoring.  asilicon valley.  asocial media.  astratification.  asurveillance.  atargeted advertising.  aubercapital.1 aHealy, Kieran, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074971740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674296688?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674296688423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674296688/original  a978-3-11-074971-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles